y or open-ended. It’s probably best to avoid CGLIB since it doesn’t seem ideal. The JDK proxy setup with metadata, though, appears to be a better fit.\\\"}]}\"}, {\"type\": \"toolCall\", \"id\": \"call_0Fvh8WgP5wjMOhvm7MPByAPI|fc_0ae71fc3b3517d92016a0c39ca2cb881a19301dd937b17d8fe\", \"name\": \"bash\", \"arguments\": {\"command\": \"grep -A4 '<artifactId>reactor-core' ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.springframework/spring-tx/7.0.3/*/spring-tx-7.0.3.pom || true; jar tf ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.springframework/spring-tx/7.0.3/*/spring-tx-7.0.3.jar | grep 'reactive/TransactionalOperator'\"}}], \"api\": \"openai-responses\", \"provider\": \"OCA\", \"model\": \"gpt-5.5\", \"usage\": {\"input\": 1521, \"output\": 819, \"cacheRead\": 33280, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"totalTokens\": 35620, \"cost\": {\"input\": 0, \"output\": 0, \"cacheRead\": 0, \"cacheWrite\": 0, \"total\": 0}}, \"stopReason\": \"toolUse\", \"timestamp\": 1779186110953, \"responseId\": \"resp_0ae71fc3b3517d92016a0c39bf6cf881a1a0c6ed6b72af137d\"}}\n14051:[recv] {\"type\": \"turn_end\", \"message\": {\"role\": \"assistant\", \"content\": [{\"type\": \"thinking\", \"thinking\": \"**Considering proxy configurations**\\n\\nI'm thinking about JDK dynamic proxies and how they relate to Spring's auto-configuration. It seems like the proxy class can be dynamically generated, but I wonder if the native setup requires specific proxy configurations from an agent. I think generated bytecode might be a bit tricky or open-ended. It’s probably best to avoid CGLIB since it doesn’t seem ideal. The JDK proxy setup with metadata, though, appears to be a better fit.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0ae71fc3b3517d92016a0c39c021b481a1a9f6e0e2d2f16ae3\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABqDDnKFu4OA6oR9mq9FWWIRclJ7IbsXNSD-LJBSFI4hjL6Sdd3lPmRIqeU2KTFddm871YJctY8KgtMeyoE97SgExjJz839UeuczVOrQE8-6GCwTJDoIo2fPLbrR2MRW2lYHLZ4Rngb09UQlvoEQrIRiEIyCPkGMeHxqjreRjsPUINatXHZ